### 3.2 Control 2: Patch Applications (ML Libraries, AI SDKs, Model Versions)

**Standard objective:** Patch applications with known vulnerabilities within 48 hours for critical, two weeks for non-critical.

**AI-specific risks:** Vulnerable ML libraries (TensorFlow, PyTorch, scikit-learn) with known CVEs; outdated AI SDKs; unpatched AI platform clients; outdated model versions.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| AI dependency inventory | Maintain a software bill of materials (SBOM) for all AI libraries and SDKs |
| Vulnerability scanning | Include AI/ML libraries in automated vulnerability scanning (e.g., Dependabot, Snyk) |
| Patching cadence | Critical AI library vulnerabilities patched within 48 hours; non-critical within 2 weeks |
| Model version tracking | Track AI model versions in use; update when vendor releases security or accuracy patches |
| Deprecation monitoring | Monitor vendor announcements for deprecated AI APIs and plan migrations |

---

### 3.3 Control 3: Configure Microsoft Office Macros (AI Plugins and Add-ins)

**Standard objective:** Block macros from the internet and only allow vetted macros in trusted locations.

**AI-specific risks:** AI plugins in Microsoft 365 accessing sensitive documents; AI add-ins with excessive permissions; malicious plugins exfiltrating data through prompt-response flows.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| AI plugin whitelist | Only allow approved AI plugins in Microsoft 365, Google Workspace, and other productivity suites |
| Permission review | Review and restrict permissions granted to AI plugins (e.g., access to emails, files, calendar) |
| Third-party add-in blocking | Block installation of third-party AI add-ins unless approved through the AI Tool Approval process |
| Copilot governance | If Microsoft Copilot is deployed, configure sensitivity label enforcement and DLP policies |
| Plugin audit | Quarterly audit of all installed AI plugins across the organisation |

---

### 3.4 Control 4: User Application Hardening (Browser Extensions, Prompt Injection Protection)

**Standard objective:** Harden web browsers and other applications to reduce the attack surface.

**AI-specific risks:** Prompt injection attacks manipulating AI outputs; AI browser extensions capturing keystrokes or clipboard data; data leakage through AI autocomplete, grammar, or translation services.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| Browser hardening | Block AI-related browser extensions not on the approved list |
| Input sanitisation | Implement prompt sanitisation for internally deployed AI models to mitigate injection attacks |
| Output filtering | Validate AI outputs before they are returned to users or integrated into business processes |
| Clipboard protection | Prevent AI tools from accessing clipboard content containing sensitive data |
| Content security policy | Configure CSP headers to prevent AI widget injection on {{ business_name }}'s web properties |

{% if customer_facing_ai %}
**Customer-facing AI note:** {{ business_name }} deploys customer-facing AI. Prompt injection protection is critical to prevent attackers from manipulating AI outputs visible to customers.
{% endif %}

---

### 3.5 Control 5: Restrict Administrative Privileges (AI Platform Admin Access)

**Standard objective:** Restrict administrative privileges to only those who need them.

**AI-specific risks:** AI platform admin accounts with excessive access; shared service accounts for AI APIs; developers with production model access.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| AI admin role separation | Separate AI platform admin roles from regular user roles |
| Least-privilege API keys | Issue AI API keys with minimum required scopes; rotate every 90 days |
| Service account governance | Audit AI service accounts quarterly; remove unused accounts immediately |
| JIT access | Implement just-in-time access for AI model deployment and configuration changes |

---

### 3.6 Control 6: Patch Operating Systems (AI Server and Endpoint Patching)

**Standard objective:** Patch operating systems with known vulnerabilities within 48 hours for critical, two weeks for non-critical.

**AI-specific risks:** Outdated OS on AI inference servers; GPU driver vulnerabilities (CUDA, ROCm); container runtime vulnerabilities in AI deployment environments.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| AI server patching | AI inference and training servers patched on the same cadence as other critical servers |
| GPU driver updates | GPU drivers updated within 2 weeks of security patches |
| Container patching | Base container images for AI workloads rebuilt and redeployed when OS patches are released |
| Cloud AI patching | Verify cloud AI service providers patch underlying infrastructure |

---

### 3.7 Control 7: Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA on All AI Platform Accounts)

**Standard objective:** MFA for all users accessing important data repositories and internet-facing services.

**AI-specific risks:** Compromised AI platform accounts enabling data exfiltration; stolen API keys; shared AI tool accounts without individual accountability.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| MFA enforcement | MFA required for all AI platform user and admin accounts without exception |
| API key protection | AI API keys stored in secrets management systems; never in source code or configuration files |
| SSO integration | Integrate AI platforms with {{ business_name }}'s identity provider (IdP) via SSO where supported |
| Session management | AI platform sessions time out after 30 minutes of inactivity |
| Shared account prohibition | No shared accounts for AI platforms; each user must have an individual account |

---

### 3.8 Control 8: Regular Backups (AI Model Configs, Training Data, Prompt Libraries)

**Standard objective:** Regular backups performed and tested for important data.

**AI-specific risks:** Loss of AI model configurations or custom model weights; loss of prompt libraries and system prompts; inability to recover AI systems to a known-good state.

**AI-specific controls:**

| Control | Implementation |
|---------|---------------|
| AI configuration backups | Back up AI model configurations, parameters, and system prompts weekly |
| Prompt library backups | Version-control and back up prompt libraries and templates |
| Training data backups | Back up proprietary training and fine-tuning datasets with integrity verification |
| Recovery testing | Test AI system recovery from backups quarterly |
| Immutable backups | Store AI backups in immutable storage to prevent ransomware encryption |

{% if ai_incident_register %}
{{ business_name }} maintains an AI incident register. Backup failures for AI systems must be logged as incidents in this register.
{% else %}
**Recommendation:** {{ business_name }} should establish an AI incident register. Backup failures for AI systems should be logged and tracked as incidents.
{% endif %}

